      <item>
        <title>Learning D3</title>
        <description>&lt;p&gt;Recently, I discovered &lt;a href=&quot;http://d3js.org/&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;D3&lt;/a&gt; a powerful Javascript library for creating beautiful and responsive data visualizations. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It works seamlessly with existing web technologies can interact with all parts of the &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.w3.org/DOM/&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;DOM&lt;/a&gt; (document object model), and is as flexible as the client side web technology stack.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;As a simple example, the chart at the bottom of the page uses spline interpolation with D3&amp;#39;s built in &lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/mbostock/d3/wiki/SVG-Axes&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;axes&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/mbostock/d3/wiki/Time-Scales&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;time scales&lt;/a&gt; to visualize your scrolling and clicking activity during your time on this page.&lt;/p&gt;
</description>
        <pubDate>Sat, 01 Nov 2014 19:47:46 -0700</pubDate>
        <link>henryachen.github.io//2014/11/01/D3/</link>
        <guid isPermaLink="true">henryachen.github.io//2014/11/01/D3/</guid>
        
        
